### Tested versions

- Godot v4.4.beta3

### System information

Windows 10 - Godot v4.4.beta3 - Vulkan(Forward+)

### Issue description

I tried to modify the Godot source code myself. I customized a class, which would export an array to the property editor, and the array element was set as a resource customized by myself. But when I finished compiling the engine and debugging, I found that the type of the array element exported in the property panel was `null`.

### Steps to reproduce

Here are my code:

<details>
<summary>comuniform.h</summary>

~~~cpp
#ifndef COMUNIFORM_H
#define COMUNIFORM_H

#include "core/io/resource.h"
#include "servers/rendering/rendering_device.h"
#include "core/variant/array.h"
#include "comaddid.h"

class ComUniform : public Resource {
	GDCLASS(ComUniform, Resource);

    public:
        RenderingDevice::UniformType uniform_type;
        RenderingDevice::UniformType get_uniform_type();
        void set_uniform_type(RenderingDevice::UniformType p_uniform_type);

        int binding = 0;
        int get_binding();
        void set_binding(int p_binding);

        // ComAddId is a resource defined by myself.
        TypedArray<ComAddId> add_ids;
        TypedArray<ComAddId> get_add_ids();
        void set_add_id(TypedArray<ComAddId> p_add_id);

        ComUniform();
        ~ComUniform();
    protected:
        static void _bind_methods();
};

#endif
~~~
</details>

<details>
  <summary>comuniform.cpp</summary>

~~~cpp
#include "comuniform.h"

RenderingDevice::UniformType ComUniform::get_uniform_type(){
    return uniform_type;
}

int ComUniform::get_binding() {
    return binding;
}

TypedArray<ComAddId> ComUniform::get_add_ids() {
    return add_ids;
}

void ComUniform::set_uniform_type(RenderingDevice::UniformType p_uniform_type) {
    uniform_type = p_uniform_type;
}

void ComUniform::set_binding(int p_binding) {
    binding = p_binding;
}

void ComUniform::set_add_id(TypedArray<ComAddId> p_add_id) {
    add_ids = p_add_id;
}

void ComUniform::_bind_methods() {
    String t = "UNIFORM_TYPE_SAMPLER, "
		"UNIFORM_TYPE_SAMPLER_WITH_TEXTURE,"
		"UNIFORM_TYPE_TEXTURE," 
		"UNIFORM_TYPE_IMAGE," 
		"UNIFORM_TYPE_TEXTURE_BUFFER,"
		"UNIFORM_TYPE_SAMPLER_WITH_TEXTURE_BUFFER,"
		"UNIFORM_TYPE_IMAGE_BUFFER,"
		"UNIFORM_TYPE_UNIFORM_BUFFER," 
		"UNIFORM_TYPE_STORAGE_BUFFER," 
		"UNIFORM_TYPE_INPUT_ATTACHMENT,"
		"UNIFORM_TYPE_MAX";
    ADD_PROPERTY(PropertyInfo(Variant::INT, "uniform_type",PROPERTY_HINT_ENUM,t), "set_uniform_type", "get_uniform_type");
    ADD_PROPERTY(PropertyInfo(Variant::INT, "binding"), "set_binding", "get_binding");
    ADD_PROPERTY(PropertyInfo(Variant::ARRAY, "add_ids",PROPERTY_HINT_ARRAY_TYPE,"ComAddId"), "set_add_id", "get_add_ids");
}

ComUniform::ComUniform() {
    add_ids.clear();
}

ComUniform::~ComUniform() {

}
~~~
</details>

The result after export is as follows:

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/bc1d8c02-36e4-4fdc-bacc-6ef6691be1a7)

But when the mouse hovers, it displays the correct type:

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/3a80f9d3-406f-44cc-9879-6a56cbca7330)

Later, I replaced A with other built-in resources of Godot, which also had this problem.

But when I use GDscript to realize this function, it works normally.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/e5467388-a3fe-4a85-a016-c6a5239150e8)

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/1b3ae9bd-31cf-49f4-9da3-680974a6197b)

So I'm not sure this is a bug. I hope you can help me look at it and give me help.



