null

### Tested versions

Problem exists in the following versions I've tested:

`Godot Engine v4.4.beta3.official (06acfccf89ad6b900ae694a4d58ceade1967a85f)` (also beta2)
`Godot Engine v4.3.stable.official.77dcf97d8`

I've not tested myself farther down the history yet.

### System information

Godot v4.4.beta3 - Windows 11 (build 26100) - Multi-window, 1 monitor - Vulkan (Forward+) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce MX250 (NVIDIA; 32.0.15.6603) - Intel(R) Core(TM) i5-10400H CPU @ 2.60GHz (8 threads)

Edit: I've retested on an entirely different computer, a Ryzen 5950x with a Radeon 6950xt and it crashes as well. Forward, Mobile and gl_compat!

### Issue description
When I was editing shaders, I got the smart idea of counting how many lights I have by introducing a varying and incrementing it in light(). Apart from that this is maybe not a good idea (ignore that part, please), when I wrote `light_count++;`, it caused an instant crash after the shader examination cycle. 

`CrashHandlerException: Program crashed with signal 11` 

When I rewrote the statement as `light_count = light_count +1` it properly showed the error `varying may not be assigned in the light function`.

I expect the `light_count++` statement to also cause the error instead of exploding on me.

### Steps to reproduce

1. Create new project
2. Create `shader` resource
3. Paste this: 
```
shader_type spatial;

varying flat int something;

void light() {
	//something++;
}

void vertex() {
	// Called for every vertex the material is visible on.
}

void fragment() {
	ALBEDO = vec3(1);
}
```
4. Uncomment `//something++;`
5. Godot crashes (I hope at least, if not then we'll have a tedious debugging process on why it crashes for me)


### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

[minimal example shader crash.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/18804335/minimal.example.shader.crash.zip)

Uncomment the `a++` line in the test.gdshader to trigger
